1. Check duplicates

In[5]:
#Multiple inpatient visits per patient
print(data.duplicated(subset=['encounter_id']).any())
print(data.duplicated(subset=['patient_nbr']).any())

False
True

The dataset contained multiple inpatient visits for some patients and the observations could not be considered as statistically independent as it violates one of the assumptions of logistic regression model. Hence, we considered only the first encounter for each patient as the primary admission and determined whether or not they were readmitted within 30 days.

In[10]:
# Replace 'None' values with 'No'
data = data.fillna('Not measured')

71,518 unique first inpatient visit is retained for further analysis.

Since these two features concern with the result of maximumm glucose level test and A1C test were taken and these tests may not be taken for some of the patient encounter, it is normal to contain none in these columns.
Instead of removing these responses, we have filled the null values with a new class "not measured" to better reflecting the situation.

def plot_selected_distributions(df, columns, sample_size=10000):
    selected_df = df[columns]  # Select only required columns

    # Sample if dataset is too large
    if len(df) > sample_size:
        selected_df = selected_df.sample(sample_size, random_state=42)

    num_cols = selected_df.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns
    cat_cols = selected_df.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns

    # Plot numerical columns (Horizontal histogram)
    if len(num_cols) > 0:
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=len(num_cols), ncols=1, figsize=(10, len(num_cols) * 3))
        if len(num_cols) == 1:
            axes = [axes]  # Ensure axes is iterable

        for i, col in enumerate(num_cols):
            sns.histplot(selected_df[col].dropna(), kde=True, ax=axes[i])
            axes[i].set_title(col)

        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

    # Plot categorical columns (Vertical count plot)
    if len(cat_cols) > 0:
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=len(cat_cols), ncols=1, figsize=(10, len(cat_cols) * 3))
        if len(cat_cols) == 1:
            axes = [axes]  # Ensure axes is iterable

        for i, col in enumerate(cat_cols):
            sns.countplot(x=selected_df[col], order=selected_df[col].value_counts().index[:10], ax=axes[i])
            axes[i].set_title(col)

        plt.xticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate x-axis labels if needed
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()


# Example: Specify 6 columns to analyze
selected_columns = ['race', 'payer_code', 'medical_specialty', 'diag_1', 'diag_2', 'diag_3']  # Replace with actual column names

# Call the function
plot_selected_distributions(data, selected_columns)

4. Fill ?

In[24]:
columns_to_replace = ['payer_code', 'medical_specialty']
data[columns_to_replace] = data[columns_to_replace].replace('?', 'Missing')

For feature "payer_code" and "medical_specialty", we decide to create a new category "Missing" to cater the "?" values.
The former feature represents the insurance coverage of the encounter and the latter represents the specialty of the admitting physician of the encounter.
We consider it being normal for these information not being disclosed during data collection as they are not compulsory to be collected in relation to the research study.

In[26]:
columns_to_fill = ["race", "diag_1", "diag_2", "diag_3"]
for col in columns_to_fill:
    mode_value = data[data[col] != "?"][col].mode()[0]  # Get the most frequent value excluding '?'
    data[col] = data[col].replace("?", mode_value)

We decide to fill "?" values in features - "race","diag_1", "diag_2", "diag_3" with mode because the proportion of "?" values is significantly lower than 3% and the distribution of the values for these features is positively skewed.
Filling the "?" values will cause the least disruption to the data.

5. Outliers check

In[29]:
def plot_outliers(df, num_vars, cat_vars):
    # Boxplots for numerical variables
    for col in num_vars:
        plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
        sns.boxplot(x=df[col])
        plt.title(f'Boxplot of {col}')
        plt.show()

    # Bar plots for categorical variables
    for col in cat_vars:
        plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
        sns.countplot(x=df[col])
        plt.title(f'Bar Plot of {col}')
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.show()

# Example usage
num_vars = data.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns.tolist() 
cat_vars = data.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns.tolist()

plot_outliers(data, num_vars, cat_vars)

Why keep the outliers:
Medical Insights: Outliers might represent rare but critical cases, such as extreme glucose levels, that could provide valuable insights into high-risk patients.

Real-World Representation: Excluding outliers may remove important variations in patient conditions, making your model less applicable to real-world scenarios.

Predictive Model Performance: If your goal is to predict extreme cases (e.g., diabetic emergencies), keeping outliers ensures the model learns from those critical instances.

Clinical Decision Support: Some outliers might indicate early warning signs of severe complications, which can be essential for medical diagnosis and treatment planning

6. Fixing diag columns

In[32]:
def categorize_icd9(code):
    try:
        code = int(float(code))  # Convert to integer if possible
    except ValueError:
        return "Other"
    
    if 390 <= code <= 459 or code == 785:
        return "Circulatory"
    elif 460 <= code <= 519 or code == 786:
        return "Respiratory"
    elif 520 <= code <= 579 or code == 787:
        return "Digestive"
    elif str(code).startswith("250"):
        return "Diabetes"
    elif 800 <= code <= 999:
        return "Injury"
    elif 710 <= code <= 739:
        return "Musculoskeletal"
    elif 580 <= code <= 629 or code == 788:
        return "Genitourinary"
    elif 140 <= code <= 239:
        return "Neoplasms"
    elif 780 <= code <= 781 or 784 == code or 790 <= code <= 799:
        return "Neoplasms"
    elif 240 <= code <= 279:
        return "Neoplasms"
    elif 680 <= code <= 709 or code == 782:
        return "Other"
    elif 1 <= code <= 139 or 290 <= code <= 319 or 280 <= code <= 289 or 320 <= code <= 359:
        return "Other"
    elif 360 <= code <= 389 or 630 <= code <= 679 or 740 <= code <= 759:
        return "Other"
    else:
        return "Other"

data[['diag_1', 'diag_2', 'diag_3']] = data[['diag_1', 'diag_2', 'diag_3']].map(categorize_icd9)
